metadata.display_name: Summary and Looking Forward: From Semiclassical to Quantum
Unit 3: What and Where is the Voltage
Unit 4: Heat & Electricity, Second Law and Information

metadata.markdown:
>>On applying a voltage, the change in the electrostatic potential doesn’t follow the electrochemical potential closely<<
     ( ) Never
     ( ) Always
     (x) if the medium has a very low density of states
     ( ) if the medium has a very high density of states
     ( )the two potentials are completely unrelated

>>In our new perspective, electrons flow because<<
( ) there is an electric field in the source and drain
( ) there is an electric field in the channel
(x) source wants to fill the channel, drain wants to empty it
( ) source and drain both want to fill the channel
( ) none of the above

>> In a ballistic transistor, where does all the heating occur?<<
     ( ) At source contact only.
     ( ) At drain contact only.
     (x) At both contacts.
     ( ) In the channel.
	 ( ) In the battery.

>>A transistor  can be viewed as a resistor with<<
( ) a third terminal to control the resistance
( ) a nonlinear current-voltage relation
(x) both (a) and (b)
( ) with all dissipation in the contacts
( ) none of the above

The reason we can write the current in an elastic resistor simply as a sum over independent energy channels is that

( )  no heat is generated inside the channel
( ) no heat is generated anywhere
(x) an electron does not change its energy inside the channel
( ) an electron does not change its energy from one terminal of the battery to the other
( ) none of the above
>>If the resistance of a probe is 4 times as large for the up spin channel as for the down spin channel, the polarization of the probe P is?<< ( ) 1/4 ( ) 1/2 (x) 3/5 ( ) 1/4 ( ) None of the above

>>In Equation (B), D(E) represents<<
     (x) the density of states
     ( ) the density of filled states
     ( ) the density of empty states
     ( ) product of (b) and (c)
     ( ) none of the above
